  "articleSummary": "The article argues that fixed priority dropdowns (e.g., P1–P4) create an escalatory \"trap\" where teams invent ever-higher levels (P0, P00) to reflect shifting priorities, leading to \"Engineering Theater\" and bloated backlogs. It critiques this as a failure to model the fluid, multidimensional nature of real-world prioritization. The tone is analytical with a frustrated, humorous edge, using metaphors like the \"z-index war\" and \"Bizzaro Trophy Room\" to illustrate the absurdity. Alternatives include unbounded numeric values, composite scoring, or dynamic methods like MoSCoW. The intended audience is software engineers, product managers, and technical leaders grappling with Jira-based backlog management.",
